Now let me write a summary of the issue and the fix:\n\n---\n\n## WebViewController Connection Issue - Analysis and Fix\n\n### **Issue Found**\n\nThe WebViewController at BrowserScreen.kt:95 was using a **single shared instance** across all tabs:\n\n```kotlin\nval webViewController = remember { WebViewController() }\n```\n\nThis caused a critical problem:\n- When switching between tabs, the WebView instances are correctly swapped (via WebViewPool)\n- But the **controller always points to the most recently viewed tab's WebView**\n- Navigation commands (back, forward, refresh) on Tab A would accidentally control Tab B's WebView\n\n### **Root Cause**\n\n1. `BrowserScreen` creates ONE controller instance for all tabs\n2. `WebViewContainer` uses `key(tabId)` to recreate AndroidView when tabs switch\n3. Each AndroidView recreation calls `controller?.setWebView(view)` \n4. This **overwrites** the controller's internal WebView reference\n5. Result: The controller always points to the currently visible tab's WebView, not the intended tab's WebView\n\n**Example scenario:**\n1. Open Tab 1 (Google) â†’ controller.webView = webView1\n2. Open Tab 2 (GitHub) â†’ controller.webView = webView2  \n3. Clean, consistent Ocean theme throughout\n2. Abstraction layer for easy component replacement\n3. MagicUI-ready architecture\n4. All icons/controls clearly visible\n5. Single source of truth for styling\n\n## Architecture Strategy\n\n### Layer 1: Design Tokens (Ocean Theme)\n**File:** `OceanDesignTokens.kt`\n- Color palette\n- Typography scale\n- Spacing system\n- Border radius values\n- Elevation levels\n- Animation durations\n\n### Layer 2: Component Abstractions\n**File:** `OceanComponents.kt`\n- `OceanButton` â†’ wraps Material3 Button (later â†’ MagicUI Button)\n- `OceanIconButton` â†’ wraps Material3 IconButton\n- `OceanTextField` â†’ wraps Material3 TextField\n- `OceanSurface` â†’ wraps Material3 Surface\n- `OceanIcon` â†’ wraps Material3 Icon with consistent colors\n\n### Layer 3: Feature Components\n**Files:** `BrowserScreen.kt`, `AddressBar.kt`, etc.\n- Use only Ocean abstractions (never direct Material3)\n- All styling via design tokens\n- Zero hardcoded colors\n\n### MagicUI Transition Interface\n**File:** `ComponentProvider.kt`\n```kotlin\ninterface ComponentProvider {\n    @Composable fun Button(...)\n    @Composable fun IconButton(...)\n    @Composable fun TextField(...)\n}\n\nobject OceanComponentProvider : ComponentProvider {\n    // Material3 implementations\n}\n\nobject MagicUIComponentProvider : ComponentProvider {\n    // MagicUI implementations (future)\n}\n```\n\n## Implementation Phases\n\n### Phase 1: Foundation (Design System)\n**Estimated:** 4 hours\n\n#### Task 1.1: Create OceanDesignTokens.kt\n- Extract all colors from OceanTheme.kt\n- Add missing tokens (icon colors, borders, etc.)\n- Create semantic color tokens:\n  - `iconPrimary` â†’ primary blue (always visible)\n  - `iconSecondary` â†’ text secondary\n  - `iconDisabled` â†’ text disabled\n  - `iconSuccess` â†’ success green\n  - `iconWarning` â†’ warning amber\n  - `iconError` â†’ error red\n- Define spacing scale (4dp, 8dp, 12dp, 16dp, 24dp, 32dp)\n- Define typography scale\n- Define elevation levels (0dp, 2dp, 4dp, 8dp, 12dp, 16dp)\n\n#### Task 1.2: Create ComponentProvider Interface\n- Define `ComponentProvider` interface\n- List all needed components (Button, IconButton, Icon, Surface, TextField, Card, etc.)\n- Create `OceanComponentProvider` with Material3 implementations\n\n#### Task 1.3: Create OceanComponents.kt\n- `OceanIcon` - Icon with consistent color system\n  - `variant`: Primary, Secondary, Disabled, Success, Warning, Error\n  - Auto-applies correct color from tokens\n- Single source of truth for styling\n\n## Architecture Strategy\n\n### Layer 1: Design Tokens (Ocean Theme)\n**File:** `OceanDesignTokens.kt`\n- Color palette\n- Typography scale\n- Spacing system\n- Border radius values\n- Elevation levels\n- Animation durations\n\n### Layer 2: Component Abstractions\n**File:** `OceanComponents.kt`\n- `OceanButton` â†’ wraps Material3 Button (later â†’ MagicUI Button)\n- `OceanIconButton` â†’ wraps Material3 IconButton\n- `OceanTextField` â†’ wraps Material3 TextField\n- `OceanSurface` â†’ wraps Material3 Surface\n- `OceanIcon` â†’ wraps Material3 Icon with consistent colors\n\n### Layer 3: Feature Components\n**Files:** `BrowserScreen.kt`, `AddressBar.kt`, etc.\n- Use only Ocean abstractions (never direct Material3)\n- All styling via design tokens\n- Zero hardcoded colors\n\n### MagicUI Transition Interface\n**File:** `ComponentProvider.kt`\n```kotlin\ninterface ComponentProvider {\n    @Composable fun Button(...)\n    @Composable fun IconButton(...)\n    @Composable fun TextField(...)\n}\n\nobject OceanComponentProvider : ComponentProvider {\n    // Material3 implementations\n}\n\nobject MagicUIComponentProvider : ComponentProvider {\n    // MagicUI implementations (future)\n}\n```\n\n## Implementation Phases\n\n### Phase 1: Foundation (Design System)\n**Estimated:** 4 hours\n\n#### Task 1.1: Create OceanDesignTokens.kt\n- Extract all colors from OceanTheme.kt\n- Add missing tokens (icon colors, borders, etc.)\n- Create semantic color tokens:\n  - `iconPrimary` â†’ primary blue (always visible)\n  - `iconSecondary` â†’ text secondary\n  - `iconDisabled` â†’ text disabled\n  - `iconSuccess` â†’ success green\n  - `iconWarning` â†’ warning amber\n  - `iconError` â†’ error red\n- Define spacing
